<TITLE> Savar workers continue demonstrations </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Savar, June 28 (bdnews24.com) The workers of the apparel factories at Ashulia on Sunday demonstrated against the death of a co-worker when Ansar personnel fired on protestors of a sweater factory the previous day. Scores of workers were injured as they clashed with the police in phases, locals said. bdnews24.com Savar correspondent reports from the spot that garments workers of Jamgarah, Narsinghpur and Beron took to the streets from the morning. The police fired rubber bullet and teargas to disperse the demonstrators. The clash suspended traffic movement on the Dhaka-Tangail highway, he said. Al Amin, a worker of S Suhi Industrial Park, was shot dead on Saturday after the Ansar personnel opened fired on the workers who were demanding a pay hike at Jamgarah. Ashulia police chief Monwar Hossain said they were trying to control the situation. The Ansar personnel had tried to pacify the demonstrators on Saturday but at one stage, they were pelted with stones. Some workers also tried to snatch arms from them, compelling them to open firing, Hossain said. He said the angry workers vandalised a factory vehicle, windows panes and doors with stones. Later, they put the Ansar camp on fire. "At around 11am the workers vandalised another eight to ten bus near Jamgara bus stand and tried to block Dhaka-Tangail highway. Police clubbed the protestors to disperse them." The Ansar men were under police custody. No-one has been arrested in connection with the killing, he added. The Savar correspondent said a group of workers on June 25 submitted an application to the management who took away attendance cards of three workers. Worker Rafiqul Islam told bdnews24.com they had fiercely argued with the management during Saturday's demonstration. The local people said the owners closed down the factory and fled the spot. The workers also left the factory fearing police reprisal. bdnews24.c
